Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Lisours II was born in 1070, in Lisors, Eure, Normandy, France, his father, Turold de Lisours, was 16 and his mother, Beatrix, was 16. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. William De Lisours."},"et":{"1070–":"1070–Surnud","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","1087–Female":"1087–Surnud","1093–Female":"1093–Surnud","1055–Male":"1055–Surnud","1055–Female":"1055–Surnud","about 1093":"umbes 1093","1055":"1055","1087":"1087","1073":"1073","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","Lisors, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Lisors, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Northamps, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1070–":"1070–Kuollut","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","1073–Female":"1073–Kuollut","1087–Female":"1087–Kuollut","1093–Female":"1093–Kuollut","1055–Male":"1055–Kuollut","1055–Female":"1055–Kuollut","about 1093":"noin 1093","1055":"1055","1087":"1087","1073":"1073","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","Lisors, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Lisors, Eure, Normandie, Ranska","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Northamps, England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1070–":"1070–Décédé","1070–Male":"1070–Décédé","1073–Female":"1073–Décédée","1087–Female":"1087–Décédée","1093–Female":"1093–Décédée","1055–Male":"1055